Business Understanding¶

Background¶

The global telecommunications industry is a vast and complex network of companies and technologies that enable communication across the globe.They had a value of $1.4 trillion in 2019. With the transition to 5G services set to take the world by storm in the next few years, the industry is expected to grow to even greater heights. It’s an exciting time for telecoms! 5G connectivity has the potential to transform the world we live in by making us more connected and our devices more intelligent.

However, for many telecom companies, more advancement and innovation means more competition for customers. It’s no secret that consumers in 2023 have exceedingly high expectations and an abundance of choices. While companies have always had to compete with customers telling their friends and family about their experiences, this is taken to another level in the digital age. Consumers take to the internet to leave reviews (both good and bad) and share their experiences on social media. We live in a fast-paced world where you can get your shopping delivered within 24 hours, get entertainment on demand, and, well, anything on demand. Consumers expect the same from every company they buy from, and telecoms is no exception.

77% of all consumers retract their loyalty more quickly than they did three years ago. This means customer retention in the telecom industry is harder to achieve than ever before.

As the industry has reached a saturation point, new customer acquisitions can’t make up for the lost ones. This further motivates ISPs and telcos to implement retention strategies. Research shows that even a 5% increase in a company’s retention rate can increase profits by 25% to 95%.

We’re going to look at how to increase customer retention in the telecom industry by analyzing the sample dataset provided by IBM. The features in the dataset, explained below, signify the customer behavior for an imaginary telecommunications company. Dataset: Telco Customer Churn

Data Dictionary¶

S.No Attribute Description
1 customerID Customer identification in the company
2 gender Whether the customer is a male or a female
3 SeniorCitizen Whether the customer is a senior citizen or not [1, 0]
4 Partner Whether the customer has a partner or not (Yes, No)
5 Dependents Whether the customer has dependents or not (Yes, No)
6 tenure Number of months the customer has stayed with the company
7 PhoneService Whether the customer has a phone service or not (Yes, No)
8 MultipleLines Whether the customer has multiple lines or not (Yes, No, No phone service)
9 InternetService Customer’s internet service provider (DSL, Fiber optic, No)
10 OnlineSecurity Whether the customer has online security or not (Yes, No, No internet service)
11 OnlineBackup Whether the customer has online backup or not (Yes, No, No internet service)
12 DeviceProtection Whether the customer has device protection or not (Yes, No, No internet service)
13 TechSupport Whether the customer has tech support or not (Yes, No, No internet service)
14 StreamingTV Whether the customer has streaming TV or not (Yes, No, No internet service)
15 StreamingMovies Whether the customer has streaming movies or not (Yes, No, No internet service)
16 Contract The contract term of the customer (Month-to-month, One year, Two year)
17 PaperlessBilling Whether the customer has paperless billing or not (Yes, No)
18 PaymentMethod The customer’s payment method (Electronic check, Mailed check, Bank transfer (automatic), Credit card (automatic))
19 MonthlyCharges The amount charged to the customer monthly
20 TotalCharges The total amount charged to the customer
21 Churn Whether the customer churned or not (Yes or No)

Problem Statement¶

Using the given dataset, build a customer churn rate prediction model for the telecommunication company which will help the company to formulate customer retention policies and services.

Objective¶

Develop a machine learning model, which will predict if a customer will stay or leave the telcoommunications company.

Checking for Imbalance class¶

In [47]:
# Checking for Imbalance class

l = list(data['Churn'].value_counts())
circle = [l[0] / sum(l) * 100,l[1] / sum(l) * 100]
blue = '#0072B2'
orange = '#D55E00'

colors = [blue, orange]
fig = plt.subplots(nrows = 1,ncols = 2,figsize = (20,5))
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.pie(circle,labels = ['Not-Churn Customer','Churn Customer'],autopct = '%1.1f%%',startangle = 90,explode = (0.1,0),colors = colors,
       wedgeprops = {'edgecolor' : 'black','linewidth': 1,'antialiased' : True})
plt.title('Churn - Not-Churn %');

plt.subplot(1,2,2)
ax = sns.countplot('Churn',data = data,palette = colors,edgecolor = 'black')
for rect in ax.patches:
    ax.text(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2, rect.get_height() + 2, rect.get_height(), horizontalalignment='center', fontsize = 11)
ax.set_xticklabels(['Not-Churn Customers','Churn Customers'])
    
plt.title('Number of Churn - Not-Churn Customers');
plt.show()

Observation:

  • Target Label is Imbalanced, where the Not-Churn Customers contribute 73.5% and Churn cutomers only contribute 26.5%.
  • The Imbalanced data will be handled by the help of SMOTE and stratified methods for the various machine learning models.

Elbow Method¶

  • We will analyze clusters from 1 to 5 and calculate the WSS scores. The WSS scores can be used to plot the Elbow Plot.

  • WSS = Within Cluster Sum of Squares

In [58]:
# Checking the inertia of our model for current k value which is 3
km_model.inertia_
Out[58]:
3707094586.3420944
In [59]:
# Create a list for clusters and scores to store the cluster groups and score for a range of 'k' using for loop
clusters = []
scores = []

for k in range(1,5):
    k_means = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state = 123)
    clusters.append(k)
    km_model = k_means.fit(data_kmc[['tenure', 'MonthlyCharges', 'TotalCharges']])
    score = km_model.inertia_
    scores.append(score)
In [60]:
# Checking the cluster groups
clusters
Out[60]:
[1, 2, 3, 4]
In [61]:
# Checking the score
scores
Out[61]:
[36146294160.38064, 7926703678.930506, 3707094586.342094, 2119061526.8403509]
In [62]:
# Store the number of clusters and their respective WSS scores a dataframe 'wss'
wss  = pd.DataFrame({'Cluster': clusters, 'Score': scores})

# Checking our dataset
wss
Out[62]:
Cluster Score
0 1 3.614629e+10
1 2 7.926704e+09
2 3 3.707095e+09
3 4 2.119062e+09
In [63]:
# Plot an Elbow plot.
wss.plot(x='Cluster', y='Score')
Out[63]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Cluster'>

Observation:

  • The point where the elbow is bended, that would be the optimal point for k. In our case we can observe that 2 is the optimal value for k.
  • Also our target feature is Churn or not-Churn, so there are only 2 classifications. Hence the optimal value for k would be 2

Silhouette Measure¶

The silhouette measure is a metric used to evaluate the quality of clustering results. It quantifies how similar a data point is to its own cluster compared to other clusters.

The silhouette score ranges from -1 to 1, where a score of 1 indicates that a data point is well matched to its own cluster and poorly matched to neighboring clusters. A score of 0 indicates that a data point is on the boundary between two clusters, and negative scores indicate that a data point is better matched to a neighboring cluster than its own.

We are using the Silhouette Measure to reconfirm that the value of k is 2 or not.

In [64]:
# Import silhouette_score from SciKit Learn library
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
In [65]:
# Using for loop, calculate the silhouette score and store in s_clusters and s_scores

s_clusters = []
s_scores = []

for k in range(2,6):
    k_means = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state = 123)
    s_clusters.append(k)
    km_model = k_means.fit(data_kmc[['tenure', 'MonthlyCharges', 'TotalCharges']])
    score = silhouette_score(data_kmc[['tenure', 'MonthlyCharges', 'TotalCharges']], km_model.labels_)
    s_scores.append(score)

[2, 3, 4, 5]

Observation:

  • We can see that the closest Silhouette score to 1 is around 0.7, for which the k value is 2.
  • This again reconfirms that the number clusters for our output feature is 2 (k=2)

Reasons for not using K-Means Cluster Model:

  • Our Target feature is "Churn Rate" and Unsupervised ML Model will not be suitable for this case.
  • Also the accuracy of using an unsupervised model for Binary Classification problem will be less compared to Supervised Models
  • We have done K-Means Cluster Model for exploring with the dataset and analysing purpose.

Train and Test splits using SMOTE (for handling imbalanced data)

SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique):
SMOTE data augmentation technique is used in machine learning to address the problem of imbalanced datasets. In SMOTE we will increase the number of cases in an imbalanced dataset to make it balanced for the training of Data Models. The synthetic examples generated by SMOTE help to balance the distribution of examples across classes, thereby improving the performance of machine learning models. SMOTE is effective for datasets where the minority class examples can be easily interpolated in the feature space.

In [86]:
# Counting the number of records for each class in train

counter = Counter(y_train)
print('Train set before',counter)

# Oversampling the train dataset using SMOTE

smt = SMOTE()
x_train_sm, y_train_sm = smt.fit_resample(x_train, y_train)


# Counting the number of records for each class in train after SMOTE

counter = Counter(y_train_sm)
print('Train set after',counter)

# Counting the number of records for each class in test

counter = Counter(y_test)
print('\n\nTest set before',counter)

# Oversampling the test dataset using SMOTE

smt = SMOTE()
x_test_sm, y_test_sm = smt.fit_resample(x_test, y_test)


# Counting the number of records for each class in test after SMOTE

counter = Counter(y_test_sm)
print('Test set after',counter)

Train set before Counter({0: 4139, 1: 1495})
Train set after Counter({0: 4139, 1: 4139})


Test set before Counter({0: 1035, 1: 374})
Test set after Counter({0: 1035, 1: 1035})

Observation: The imbalanced data for Churn vs non-churn output feature has been balanced using SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) Analysis. We will use this balanced dataset to train our Data Models

Logistic Regression:¶

Logistic regression is a statistical method used in machine learning for binary classification problems. It is a type of generalized linear model (GLM) that uses a logistic function to model the relationship between a set of input features and a binary output variable.

In our problem we are using logistic regression to estimate the probability of the Churn and non-churn classes with our set of input features.

Highlights of LR Model:¶

The logistic regression model is trained by minimizing a cost function, such as the binary cross-entropy loss, using an optimization algorithm such as gradient descent. During training, the model adjusts the weights to minimize the difference between the predicted probabilities and the actual labels in the training data.

Once trained, the logistic regression model can be used to make predictions on new data by computing the predicted probability of the positive class given the input features, and then using a decision threshold to assign a binary label.

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

# generate evaluation metrics

#Accuracy

#Area under curve

#Confusion matrix of test

#Classification report of test

weighted avg       0.79      0.78      0.78      2070

Observation:

  • The accuracy of the model on both the training and test set has decreased after applying SMOTE. This may be because SMOTE introduces synthetic examples, which may not always be reliable (for certain models), and may make the model more prone to overfitting.

  • The AUC score is the same as the accuracy score because the classes are now balanced in the dataset. AUC is a measure of the model's ability to distinguish between positive and negative examples, so it is important to evaluate the AUC score when the classes are imbalanced.

  • The confusion matrix shows that the model is better at predicting the positive class (1) after applying SMOTE, with more true positives than false positives. However, the model still has more false negatives than false positives.

  • The classification report indicates that the precision, recall, and F1 score are similar for both classes after applying SMOTE, suggesting that the model is more balanced in its predictions.

    Overall, applying SMOTE has improved the model's ability to predict the positive class (1), but has decreased its accuracy on both the training and test sets.

Decision Tree Classification¶

Decision Tree Classification is a machine learning algorithm that builds a tree-like model for making decisions based on a set of rules learned from the data. The algorithm recursively splits the data into subsets based on the values of input features until it reaches a point where all the instances in a subset belong to the same class. The algorithm splits the data based on the feature that provides the best information gain

In [96]:

Random Forrest Classification¶

Random Forest Classification is a supervised learning algorithm used for classification tasks. It is an ensemble learning algorithm that creates multiple decision trees and combines their outputs to make the final prediction. Random Forest overcomes the overfitting problem by randomly selecting a subset of features and a subset of data to train each decision tree.

In [105]:

Accuracy scores: [0.77415459 0.80736715 0.90157005 0.90271903 0.91722054]

Mean accuracy: 0.8606062728957777

Standard deviation: 0.05824944457521924

Observation:

  • The accuracy scores of the model on each fold of the cross-validation are [0.77415459 0.80736715 0.90157005 0.90271903 0.91722054].
  • The mean accuracy score of the model across all folds is 0.8606, which indicates that the model is performing reasonably well on average.
  • However, it is also important to consider the standard deviation of the accuracy scores, which is 0.0558.
  • A high standard deviation indicates that the model's performance varies significantly across different folds of the cross-validation. In this case, the standard deviation is relatively low, which suggests that the model is consistent in its performance across the different folds.

    Overall, it seems that the Random Forest model with SMOTE is performing well

Support Vector Machine¶

A Support Vector Machine (SVM) is a supervised learning algorithm used for classification problems. SVMs are used for binary classification problems, that is, when the target variable is binary (1/0, True/False, Yes/No).
The algorithm separates the data into classes by finding the optimal hyperplane that maximizes the margin between the two classes. The margin is the distance between the hyperplane and the closest data points from each class. The SVM algorithm seeks to find the hyperplane that has the maximum margin between the two classes while minimizing the classification error.

SVM is a powerful algorithm that can handle complex data and is widely used in various fields.

In [114]:
from sklearn.svm import SVC

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

  • Hyperparameter tuning is the process of selecting the optimal combination of hyperparameters for a machine learning algorithm in order to maximize its performance on a given task.
  • Hyperparameters are parameters that are not learned from the data but are set manually or through a search process, such as the learning rate in gradient descent or the number of trees in a random forest.
  • Hyperparameter tuning is important because selecting the wrong values can lead to poor performance or even cause the model to overfit or underfit the data
  • There are several methods for hyperparameter tuning, including grid search, random search, etc.
  • It is an important step in building accurate and effective machine learning models.
  • By selecting the right hyperparameters, we can improve the performance of our models and ensure that they are robust and generalizable.

Logistic Regression¶

In [123]:
# Grid searching key hyperparameters for logistic regression

from sklearn.datasets import make_blobs
from sklearn.model_selection import RepeatedStratifiedKFold
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

# Create object of the class

LRmodel_hpt = LogisticRegression()

# Parameters

solvers = ['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'liblinear']
penalty = ['l2']
c_values = [100, 10, 1.0, 0.1, 0.01]


# Define grid search

grid = dict(solver=solvers,penalty=penalty,C=c_values)
cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, n_repeats=3, random_state=123)
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=LRmodel_hpt, param_grid=grid, n_jobs=-1, cv=cv, scoring='accuracy',error_score=0)
grid_result = grid_search.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Results

print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_))
means = grid_result.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = grid_result.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = grid_result.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    print("%f (%f) with: %r" % (mean, stdev, param))

# Grid searching key hyperparameters for Decision Tree Classification

    'max_depth': [2, 3, 5, 10, 20],
    'min_samples_leaf': [5, 10, 20, 50, 100],
    'criterion': ["gini", "entropy"],
    'max_features': [10,15,20,25,30]
}

Testing model with best parameters

In [130]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
# Create an object of the class

# Using the best parameters from gridsearch

DecisionTreeClassifier_tuned = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=10, max_features=30,criterion='entropy',min_samples_leaf=100)

# Train your model

DTmodel_tuned = DecisionTreeClassifier_tuned.fit(x_train,y_train)

#Prediction

#Train set
DT_y_pred_train_tuned = DTmodel_tuned.predict(x_train) 

#Test set
DT_y_pred_test_tuned = DTmodel_tuned.predict(x_test)

# generate evaluation metrics

#Accuracy
print ("\nTrain Accuracy after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.accuracy_score(y_train, DT_y_pred_train_tuned))
print ("\nTest Accuracy after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, DT_y_pred_test_tuned))

#Area under curve
print ("\nTrain AUC after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.roc_auc_score(y_train, DT_y_pred_train_tuned))
print ("\nTest AUC after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, DT_y_pred_test_tuned))

#Confusion matrix of test
print ("\nConfusion matrix after Hyperparameter tuning:\n\n",metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test,DT_y_pred_test_tuned))

#Classification report of test
print ("\nclassification report after Hyperparameter tuning:\n\n\n", metrics.classification_report(y_test,DT_y_pred_test_tuned))

Observation:

  • The results show that the model achieved a train accuracy of 0.8058 and a test accuracy of 0.7970.

  • The train and test AUC scores after hyperparameter tuning are 0.6932 and 0.6740, respectively, indicating that the model's ability to distinguish between positive and negative classes is not very high.

  • The confusion matrix shows that the model correctly classified 969 instances of the negative class and 154 instances of the positive class, while incorrectly classifying 220 instances of the positive class and 66 instances of the negative class.

  • The classification report shows that the precision of the model is 0.81 for the negative class and 0.70 for the positive class, while the recall is 0.94 for the negative class and 0.41 for the positive class. The F1-score is 0.87 for the negative class and 0.52 for the positive class.

    Overall, the model seems to perform reasonably well on the negative class, but not as well on the positive class. It may be worth exploring other classification models.

Using SMOTE train-test-split

In [132]:
# Grid searching key hyperparameters for Decision Tree Classification

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

# Create object of the class

DTmodel_hpt = DecisionTreeClassifier()

# Parameters

params = {
    'max_depth': [2, 3, 5, 10, 20],
    'min_samples_leaf': [5, 10, 20, 50, 100],
    'criterion': ["gini", "entropy"],
    'max_features': [10,15,20,25,30]
}



# Define grid search

cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, n_repeats=3, random_state=123)
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=DTmodel_hpt, param_grid=params, n_jobs=-1, cv=cv, scoring='accuracy',error_score=0)
grid_result = grid_search.fit(x_train_sm, y_train_sm)

# Results

print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_))
means = grid_result.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = grid_result.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = grid_result.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    print("%f (%f) with: %r" % (mean, stdev, param))

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
# Create an object of the class

# Using the best parameters from gridsearch

DecisionTreeClassifier_tuned_sm = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=10, max_features=30,criterion='entropy',min_samples_leaf=10, random_state= 123)

# Train your model

DTmodel_tuned_sm = DecisionTreeClassifier_tuned_sm.fit(x_train_sm,y_train_sm)

#Prediction

#Train set
DT_y_pred_train_tuned_sm = DTmodel_tuned_sm.predict(x_train_sm) 

#Test set
DT_y_pred_test_tuned_sm = DTmodel_tuned_sm.predict(x_test_sm)

# generate evaluation metrics

#Accuracy
print ("\nTrain Accuracy after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.accuracy_score(y_train_sm, DT_y_pred_train_tuned_sm))
print ("\nTest Accuracy after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.accuracy_score(y_test_sm, DT_y_pred_test_tuned_sm))

#Area under curve
print ("\nTrain AUC after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.roc_auc_score(y_train_sm, DT_y_pred_train_tuned_sm))
print ("\nTest AUC after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test_sm, DT_y_pred_test_tuned_sm))

#Confusion matrix of test
print ("\nConfusion matrix after Hyperparameter tuning:\n\n",metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test_sm,DT_y_pred_test_tuned_sm))

#Classification report of test
print ("\nclassification report after Hyperparameter tuning:\n\n\n", metrics.classification_report(y_test_sm,DT_y_pred_test_tuned_sm))

Observation:

  • The accuracy score for the training set is 0.835, indicating that the model has learned the training data well.
  • The accuracy score for the test set is 0.769, which means that the model is able to generalize to new data, although there is still some room for improvement.
  • The AUC score is the same as the accuracy score, indicating that the model is not very good at distinguishing between the two classes.
  • The confusion matrix shows that the model is better at predicting the positive class (1) than the negative class (0).
  • The precision and recall scores are both around 0.76-0.79 for both classes, which means that the model is reasonably good at identifying true positives but also generates false positives and false negatives.

Overall, it seems that the model could still benefit from further optimization to improve its performance and it is not good as Random Forest Model

# Grid searching key hyperparameters for Random Forrest Classification

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# Create object of the class

RFmodel_hpt = RandomForestClassifier()

# Parameters

params = {
    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 200],
    'max_depth': [2, 3, 5, 10, 20],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10, 15],
    'criterion': ["gini", "entropy"],
    'min_samples_leaf': [5, 10, 20, 50, 100] 
}


# Define grid search

cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, n_repeats=3, random_state=123)
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=RFmodel_hpt, param_grid=params, n_jobs=-1, cv=cv, scoring='accuracy',error_score=0)
grid_result = grid_search.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Results

print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_))
means = grid_result.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = grid_result.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = grid_result.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    print("%f (%f) with: %r" % (mean, stdev, param))

Testing the model with best parameters

In [136]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
# create an object of the class

# Using the best parameters from gridsearch

RandomForestClassifier_tuned = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, criterion='entropy', max_depth=10, min_samples_leaf=5, min_samples_split=10, random_state=123)

# Train your model

RFmodel_tuned = RandomForestClassifier_tuned.fit(x_train,y_train)

#Prediction

#Train set
RF_y_pred_train_tuned = RFmodel_tuned.predict(x_train) 

#Test set
RF_y_pred_test_tuned = RFmodel_tuned.predict(x_test)

# generate evaluation metrics

#Accuracy
print ("\nTrain Accuracy after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.accuracy_score(y_train, RF_y_pred_train_tuned))
print ("\nTest Accuracy after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, RF_y_pred_test_tuned))

#Area under curve
print ("\nTrain AUC after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.roc_auc_score(y_train, RF_y_pred_train_tuned))
print ("\nTest AUC after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, RF_y_pred_test_tuned))    

#Confusion matrix of test
print ("\nConfusion matrix after Hyperparameter tuning:\n\n",metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test,RF_y_pred_test_tuned))

#Classification report of test
print ("\nclassification report after Hyperparameter tuning:\n\n\n", metrics.classification_report(y_test,RF_y_pred_test_tuned))

Using SMOTE train-test-split

In [139]:
# Grid searching key hyperparameters for Random Forrest Classification

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# Create object of the class

RFmodel_hpt_sm = RandomForestClassifier()

# Parameters

params = {
    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 200],
    'max_depth': [2, 3, 5, 10, 20],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10, 15],
    'criterion': ["gini", "entropy"],
    'min_samples_leaf': [5, 10, 20, 50, 100] 
}


# Define grid search

cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, n_repeats=3, random_state=123)
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=RFmodel_hpt_sm, param_grid=params, n_jobs=-1, cv=cv, scoring='accuracy',error_score=0)
grid_result = grid_search.fit(x_train_sm, y_train_sm)

# Results

print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_))
means = grid_result.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = grid_result.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = grid_result.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    print("%f (%f) with: %r" % (mean, stdev, param))

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
# create an object of the class

# Using the best parameters from gridsearch

RandomForestClassifier_tuned_sm = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=200, criterion='entropy', max_depth=20, min_samples_leaf=5, min_samples_split=2, random_state=123)

# Train your model

RFmodel_tuned_sm = RandomForestClassifier_tuned_sm.fit(x_train_sm,y_train_sm)

#Prediction

#Train set
RF_y_pred_train_tuned_sm = RFmodel_tuned_sm.predict(x_train_sm) 

#Test set
RF_y_pred_test_tuned_sm = RFmodel_tuned_sm.predict(x_test_sm)

# generate evaluation metrics

#Accuracy
print ("\nTrain Accuracy after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.accuracy_score(y_train_sm, RF_y_pred_train_tuned_sm))
print ("\nTest Accuracy after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.accuracy_score(y_test_sm, RF_y_pred_test_tuned_sm))

#Area under curve
print ("\nTrain AUC after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.roc_auc_score(y_train_sm, RF_y_pred_train_tuned_sm))
print ("\nTest AUC after Hyperparameter tuning:", metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test_sm, RF_y_pred_test_tuned_sm))    

#Confusion matrix of test
print ("\nConfusion matrix after Hyperparameter tuning:\n\n",metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test_sm,RF_y_pred_test_tuned_sm))

#Classification report of test
print ("\nclassification report after Hyperparameter tuning:\n\n\n", metrics.classification_report(y_test_sm,RF_y_pred_test_tuned_sm))

# Grid searching key hyperparameters for Support Vector Machine

from sklearn.svm import SVC

# Create object of the class

SVCmodel_hpt = SVC(probability=True)

# Parameters

params = {
    'kernel': ['poly', 'rbf', 'sigmoid'],
    'C': [50, 10, 1.0, 0.1, 0.01],
    'gamma': ['scale','auto']
}


# Define grid search

cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, n_repeats=3, random_state=123)
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=SVCmodel_hpt, param_grid=params, n_jobs=-1, cv=cv, scoring='accuracy',error_score=0)
grid_result = grid_search.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Results

print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_))
means = grid_result.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = grid_result.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = grid_result.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    print("%f (%f) with: %r" % (mean, stdev, param))

Ensemble Learning¶

Ensemble learning is a technique in machine learning where multiple models are combined to improve the overall performance and accuracy of the system. It is based on the idea that combining the predictions of several models is often more accurate than relying on the predictions of a single model.

Ensemble Voting
Ensemble voting is a technique in machine learning that combines the predictions of multiple models to make a final prediction. It is a type of ensemble learning where multiple models are trained independently and their results are aggregated to improve the overall performance of the model. There are two types of ensemble voting:

  • Hard Voting: In hard voting, the predictions of each model are counted and the majority prediction is taken as the final prediction.

  • Soft Voting: In soft voting, the predicted probabilities of each model are averaged and the class with the highest probability is taken as the final prediction.

We are using Ensemble voting in our decision tree, logistic regression, support vector machines, and random forest model.

In [152]:
#!pip install mlxtend 
# If not already installed

Ensemble Voting on Classifiers without Smote

In [153]:
from mlxtend.classifier import EnsembleVoteClassifier

clfs = [] #List to hold the Classifiers

#To Store the Prediction
eHardVoting_y_pred_test = []
eSoftVoting_y_pred_test = []

# Hard Voting
ECH = EnsembleVoteClassifier(clfs=[LRmodel, DTmodel, SVCmodel,RFmodel,LRmodel_tuned,DTmodel_tuned,RFmodel_tuned,SVCmodel_tuned], voting='hard')
# Soft Voting with equal weights given for each classifier
ECS = EnsembleVoteClassifier(clfs=[LRmodel, DTmodel, SVCmodel,RFmodel,LRmodel_tuned,DTmodel_tuned,RFmodel_tuned,SVCmodel_tuned], voting='soft', weights=[1,1,1,1,2,2,3,2])

for clf, label in zip([ECH, ECS], 
                      ['Ensemble Hard Voting', 
                       'Ensemble Soft Voting']):
    #Cross-Validation for Evaluation
    scores = cross_val_score(clf, x_train, y_train, cv=StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5), scoring='accuracy')
    print("Train CV Accuracy: %0.4f (+/- %0.4f) [%s]" % (scores.mean(), scores.std(), label))
    md = clf.fit(x_train, y_train)    
    clfs.append(md)
    if label == 'Ensemble Hard Voting':
        eHardVoting_y_pred_test = clf.predict(x_test)
    elif label == 'Ensemble Soft Voting':
        eSoftVoting_y_pred_test = clf.predict(x_test)
    print("Test Accuracy: %0.4f " % (metrics.accuracy_score(clf.predict(x_test), y_test)))

Train CV Accuracy: 0.8028 (+/- 0.0093) [Ensemble Hard Voting]
Test Accuracy: 0.8006 
Train CV Accuracy: 0.8033 (+/- 0.0064) [Ensemble Soft Voting]
Test Accuracy: 0.8027

Observation:
Ensemble Voting without SMOTE:

The results indicate that soft voting performs better than hard voting. The test accuracy of the soft voting ensemble is slightly higher than the hard voting ensemble. This suggests that combining the outputs of the classifiers using weighted average (soft voting) can improve the performance of the ensemble.

The train CV accuracy scores are consistent and relatively high for both ensemble methods, with small standard deviations. This suggests that the models are generalizing well and are not overfitting to the training data.

Overall, the observations suggest that the ensemble methods are effective for the given classification task, and using soft voting can lead to better performance than hard voting. However, the absence of SMOTE may lead to some concerns about the performance on imbalanced datasets.

Ensemble Voting on Classifiers with Smote

In [154]:
clfs_sm = [] #List to hold the Classifiers

#To Store the Prediction
eHardVoting_y_pred_test_sm = []
eSoftVoting_y_pred_test_sm = []

# Hard Voting
ECH_sm = EnsembleVoteClassifier(clfs=[LRmodel_sm,DTmodel_sm,SVCmodel_sm,LRmodel_tuned_sm,DTmodel_tuned_sm,SVCmodel_tuned_sm], voting='hard')
# Soft Voting with equal weights given for each classifier
ECS_sm = EnsembleVoteClassifier(clfs=[LRmodel_sm,DTmodel_sm,SVCmodel_sm,LRmodel_tuned_sm,DTmodel_tuned_sm,SVCmodel_tuned_sm], voting='soft', weights=[1,1,1,2,2,2])
#RFmodel with HyperParameter Tuning & Smote is not included

for clf, label in zip([ECH_sm, ECS_sm], 
                      ['Ensemble Hard Voting with Smote', 
                       'Ensemble Soft Voting with Smote']):
    #Cross-Validation for Evaluation
    scores = cross_val_score(clf, x_train_sm, y_train_sm, cv=StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5), scoring='accuracy')
    print("Train CV Accuracy: %0.4f (+/- %0.4f) [%s]" % (scores.mean(), scores.std(), label))
    md_sm = clf.fit(x_train_sm, y_train_sm)   
    clfs_sm.append(md_sm)
    if label == 'Ensemble Hard Voting with Smote':
        eHardVoting_y_pred_test_sm = clf.predict(x_test_sm)
    elif label == 'Ensemble Soft Voting with Smote':
        eSoftVoting_y_pred_test_sm = clf.predict(x_test_sm)
    print("Test Accuracy: %0.4f " % (metrics.accuracy_score(clf.predict(x_test_sm), y_test_sm)))

Train CV Accuracy: 0.8027 (+/- 0.0255) [Ensemble Hard Voting with Smote]
Test Accuracy: 0.7860 
Train CV Accuracy: 0.8247 (+/- 0.0381) [Ensemble Soft Voting with Smote]
Test Accuracy: 0.8039

Observation: The results indicate that using SMOTE can improve the performance of the models. Both hard voting and soft voting ensemble methods with SMOTE have higher train CV accuracy and test accuracy than the previous models without SMOTE. This suggests that SMOTE is effective in handling the imbalanced dataset and can improve the classification performance.

The soft voting ensemble with SMOTE has a slightly higher train CV accuracy and test accuracy than the hard voting ensemble with SMOTE. This is consistent with the previous observations, which suggest that soft voting can improve the performance of the ensemble.

The train CV accuracy scores for the ensemble methods with SMOTE have larger standard deviations than the previous models without SMOTE. This may indicate that the models are overfitting to some extent, but the overall performance is still good.

Overall, the observations suggest that using SMOTE can improve the performance of ensemble methods on imbalanced datasets. Soft voting may lead to slightly better performance than hard voting.

  • However, when SMOTE is applied to the LR model, the F1 score slightly decreases to 0.7832.
  • This suggests that oversampling of the minority class using SMOTE did not significantly improve the performance of the LR model in this case.
  • Similarly, applying hyperparameter tuning to the SMOTE-augmented LR model does not seem to provide any additional performance benefits.

  • Logistic Regression and Logistic Regression with Smote both have the same AUC score of 0.84, which means both models have similar prediction power.
  • Logistic Regression with Hyperparameter tuning has a slightly higher AUC score of 0.86, indicating better performance compared to the previous two models.
  • Logistic Regression with Hyperparameter tuning and Smote has the same AUC score of 0.86 as the previous model with Hyperparameter tuning, indicating that Smote did not improve the performance of the model in terms of AUC score. However, Smote might have improved other metrics such as F1 score or recall.

Overall, it can be concluded that Logistic Regression with Hyperparameter tuning performed the best among the four models in terms of AUC score.

  • The Random Forest Classification model with both hyperparameter tuning and SMOTE sampling has the highest AUC value of 0.90, indicating that this model is the most accurate in distinguishing between the positive and negative classes.

Overall, it can be observed that the ensemble models with SMOTE have higher F1 scores than the ensemble models without SMOTE. The soft voting strategy performs slightly better than the hard voting strategy.

import chart_studio.plotly as py
from plotly.offline import init_notebook_mode, iplot
init_notebook_mode(connected=True)
import plotly.graph_objs as go
import itertools

scoresf1=[LR_f1,LR_f1_sm,LR_f1_tuned,LR_f1_tuned_sm,DT_f1,DT_f1_sm,DT_f1_tuned,DT_f1_tuned_sm,RF_f1,RF_f1_sm,RF_f1_tuned,RF_f1_tuned_sm,SVC_f1,SVC_f1_sm,SVC_f1_tuned,SVC_f1_tuned_sm,EnsembleHardVoting_f1,EnsembleSoftVoting_f1,EnsembleHardVotingwithSmote_f1,EnsembleSoftVotingwithSmote_f1]

#create traces

Algorithms=["LR","LR_SMOTE","LR_HYP","LR_SMOTE_HYP","DT","DT_SMOTE","DT_HYP","DT_SMOTE_HYP","RF","RF_SMOTE","RF_HYP","RF_SMOTE_HYP","SVM","SVM_SMOTE","SVM_HYP","SVM_SMOTE_HYP","ENSEMBLE_HV","EN_SV","EN_HV_SMOTE","EN_SV_SMOTE"]

trace1 = go.Scatter(x = Algorithms,y= scoresf1,name='Algorithms',marker =dict(color='rgba(225,126,0,0.5)',line =dict(color='rgb(0,0,0)',width=2)),text=Algorithms)

data = [trace1]

layout = go.Layout(barmode = "group", xaxis= dict(title= 'Algorithms',ticklen= 5,zeroline= False),yaxis= dict(title= 'Prediction Scores (F1)',ticklen= 5,zeroline= False))

fig = go.Figure(data = data, layout = layout)

iplot(fig)
In [182]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

scoresf1=[LR_f1,LR_f1_sm,LR_f1_tuned,LR_f1_tuned_sm,DT_f1,DT_f1_sm,DT_f1_tuned,DT_f1_tuned_sm,RF_f1,RF_f1_sm,RF_f1_tuned,RF_f1_tuned_sm,SVC_f1,SVC_f1_sm,SVC_f1_tuned,SVC_f1_tuned_sm]

Algorithms=["LR","LR_SMOTE","LR_HYP","LR_SMOTE_HYP","DT","DT_SMOTE","DT_HYP","DT_SMOTE_HYP","RF","RF_SMOTE","RF_HYP","RF_SMOTE_HYP","SVM","SVM_SMOTE","SVM_HYP","SVM_SMOTE_HYP"]

# create a dictionary of algorithm names and corresponding f1 scores
alg_scores_dict = dict(zip(Algorithms, scoresf1))

# create a dataframe from the dictionary
df = pd.DataFrame(alg_scores_dict.items(), columns=['Algorithm', 'F1 Score'])

# create the barplot using seaborn
sns.set_style("whitegrid")
sns.barplot(x="Algorithm", y="F1 Score", data=df, palette="husl")
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.xlabel('Algorithm')
plt.ylabel('F1 Score')
plt.title('Comparison of F1 Scores for Different Algorithms')
plt.show()

Model Selection analysis¶

  • As it is clearly visible from the above chart Random Forest Classification is the best machine learning algorithm for the dataset used.

  • Imbalanced data was a big factor in lower accuracies. SMOTE was a good booster for the model as it converted the data to a more balanced state.

  • Hyperparameter tuning really enhanced the model with best parameters to predict the churn rate.

  • Random Forrest Classification SMOTE with Hyperparameter tuning is the best model with the highest accuracy of all models.

Conclusion¶

Random Forrest Classification is the best model with an accuracy of 80.8%

Results analysis¶

  • Among all the models, the Random Forest Classification with Hyperparameter and SMOTE sampling has the highest F1 score of 0.8159, indicating that this model is the most accurate in predicting the target variable.
  • Random Forest Classification with SMOTE sampling also performed well with an F1 score of 0.8010, indicating that oversampling the minority class using SMOTE has improved the performance of the model.
  • The Ensemble models (both Hard and Soft Voting) with SMOTE sampling have higher F1 scores than the corresponding models without ensemble voting.
  • Logistic Regression and Decision Tree Classification models perform similarly and have lower F1 scores than other models.
  • SVM Classification models have moderate F1 scores and have performed better with the addition of SMOTE sampling.

Overall, the Random Forest model with Hyperparameter tuning and SMOTE sampling is the best-performing model, followed closely by the Ensemble Soft Voting with SMOTE sampling model.

Recommendation:¶

We can use XG Boost with SMOTE, which will improve the overall performance of all the models and will increase the accuracy as well.
